  title: Epitaph for Minister Choe of Wansan, Posthumously Named Munjin, Grand Commandant of the Koryŏ State
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Choe clan of Wansan traces its lineage to ancestors of note. Among them was Choe Sunaek, who rose to Inspector General of the Divine Tiger Guard. He fathered Choe Sung, a Colonel. The Colonel fathered Nam-bu, who attained the rank of Grand Commandant of the Left and Right Guards and Minister of Works. The Minister fathered Choe Chŏn, a Colonel of the Left and Right Guards. The Colonel fathered Choe Chŏngsin, a Major of the Left and Right Guards. The Major fathered Choe Tŭkpyŏng, who became Grand Counselor, Director of the Ministry of Selection, and High Commander in Retirement. He was noted for his integrity and self-discipline, commanding respect and awe from all. Through the reigns of Kings Chungnyŏl, Chungson, and Chungsuk he served with distinction, and King Chungson held him in particularly high regard. Though Chungson had abdicated, he retained influence in state affairs, and many of the promotions and dismissals of officials came through his hand. When Tŭkpyŏng oversaw the Censorate, its discipline flourished. When he served in the Ministry of Justice, punishments became equitable. As governor of Gimhae and Sangju, the people cherished his benevolence. When he twice inspected Jeolla Province as Censor, the people reverenced his bearing. In the land survey he assisted Chancellor Chae Hongchŏl in dividing Jeolla's territories fairly, neither abandoning law nor disturbing the people. He lived seventy-five years.

    Tŭkpyŏng married the daughter of Kŏk Ye, Vice Director of the Privy Council and Scholar of the Secretariat, and from her was born our subject on the fourth month, cyclical year Kyemyo, day Kyeyu. The subject was named Chae, styled Chaechiji. In the year Chichi, he was appointed Registrar of the Great Compassion Temple. In Taejeong's cyclical year Kapcja, he entered the Imperial Secretariat. Four years later he received a minor appointment, and the following year became Deputy Commander. In Chŏnnyŏk's cyclical year Kyŏngho, alongside the lords An Mungae and Yi Tam who presided over the examinations, he achieved success. Six years later he was appointed Vice Magistrate of Tanyang. Four years after that he finally received appointment as Chief of the Central Ministry, gaining the rank of Court Official. Shortly thereafter he became magistrate of Sŏzjou, but declined to take office, choosing instead to complete his filial mourning. The following year King Chungsuk, pruning unnecessary officials, had someone recommend him. The king declared: "I well know his father's integrity and principles—there is no one comparable." He was appointed Censor, though reluctant to serve. When King Kongmin ascended, he was stripped of office.

    When the Koryŏ clan's rebellion erupted, all the king's appointments were reformed. A Military Commission was established with him as judge. Greatly displeased, he feigned illness and refused to appear. His superiors pressed and threatened him. At last he came forth and said to the Vice Chancellor: "The king has indeed lost virtue, yet for a minister to expose the king's failings—can this sit easy in one's heart? The king's wrongs do not originate from him alone; those around him flatter and encourage them. First they are received, then later exposed—this I find shameful." The Chancellor remained silent, daring not to speak.

    When King Kongmok ascended, he was appointed Secretary of Laws in the initial government. That winter he went out as magistrate of Hŭngju. He undertook every measure to benefit the people. Finding the land registers corrupted and decayed, he restored them, comparing them with the original records. Those who heard of this marveled. When the Commissioner of Officials gained power, jealous of him, he was transferred. In the year Chŏnghae, when Commissioners Wang Huk and Kim Yŏngdon received royal mandate to settle land disputes, they nominated him as judge and sent post horses to summon him urgently. Upon his arrival they said again: "Changhŭng Province is now notorious as difficult to govern—only Choe can manage it." Yet another opportunity presented itself: his maternal uncle Kŏk Yŏngjun held office, requiring him to recuse himself. He was transferred to Secretary of Laws.

    In the year Mucha, he became Inspector of Gyeongsang Province. In one year he was twice promoted: to Vice Minister of Rites and Commissioner of Resources. Managing both internal and external expenditures, he returned all surplus to the people, eliminating former abuses. In the year Kichuk, he became magistrate of Yangju. A royal envoy bearing incense saw the Regional Inspector treated with contempt. "This violates propriety," he declared. "It will soon touch me." He resigned and departed. Officials, pleased, recommended him for appointment as Supreme Censor—the Censorate's vigor was restored—though his tenure lasted but a year.

    In the year Sinmyo, when King Kongmin ascended, he was reappointed Supreme Censor. The following year he moved to Minor Prefect of Kaesŏng, then resigned and retired to Cheongju as the Day-new rebellion erupted. In the year Kapo, he was summoned again as Chief Secretary of Laws. Soon after he transferred to the Ministry of Lands. That autumn he went out as magistrate of Fukzhou, observing the people's condition and honoring agreements. When he departed, the people grieved as if orphaned. His beneficent works are followed to this day.

    In autumn of the year Eulmi, he was summoned as Vice Censor and Keeper of the Precious Writings Archive. The military land allotment system was ancient, but fraught with complexity—one person received land, passed it to descendants or saw it taken by others; disputes arose constantly. "Should we make the people compete and rob each other?" he asked. He decreed that only the rightful claimant receive land, greatly simplifying litigation. In the year Byŏngsin, he was appointed Vice Minister of Works. In the year Chŏngyuk, he ascended to Minister of the Great Storehouse. At fifty-five, his resolve undiminished, he applied himself with renewed vigor—the granaries filled within a month. King Kongmin declared: "The Minister of the Storehouse who fulfills his office is Choe alone."

    In the year Kihae, he became magistrate of Kongju, showing the same care for the people as in Fukzhou. In the year Sinchuk, he was appointed magistrate of Sangju. That winter, fleeing conflict, the court moved southward. The following spring the king visited Sangju; with utmost diligence he provided for all needs while trembling lest even a hair's worth burden the people—some grumbled at unmet requests. In the third month, as Minister of Laws with divided service in the capital, he requested leave. The king received him in audience, offering gentle words of comfort.

    In the year Kachin, he was appointed Vice Minister of the Censorate and Lecturer of the Royal Academy. That winter he was enfeoffed as Grand Commandant of Wansan. The following year he became Minister of Lands; the year after, Prefect of Kaesŏng. In the year Kiyuk, the new official system took effect; he was reclassified as Grand Commandant. In the year Sinhae, the position of magistrate of Andong fell vacant. "I have already found the right man," the king declared, sending guards to urge him to take office—fearing he might refuse. In spring of the year Kabin, citing his age, he requested retirement to his native place. That autumn in the ninth month, King Kongmin passed away. He attended the mourning rites with utmost grief.

    The current sovereign appointed him Vice Minister of the Privy Council, but he steadfastly declined, requesting to return home. He was enfeoffed as Lord of Wansan with the rank of Grand Commandant. The following spring he was ordered to travel to see Censor Choe Anso in Kangnung and return—a final farewell. In the ninth month, a slight illness befell him. He told his sons: "I once dreamed that a mysterious being told me I would die in the Year of the Horse. This is now the year of the Horse, and I am thus afflicted. I shall not recover." On the tenth month, cyclical day Kisa, he passed away at seventy-six. On the twelfth month, cyclical day Imyin, he was interred east of his residence, fulfilling his final wishes.

    Ah, Choe could be called a sage who transcended the vulgar and remained untroubled by worldly affairs! He married twice: Lady Sim of Yŏngsan, daughter of Minister Sin Che, and Lady Park of Muan, daughter of Military Official Park Yunryu. By Sim he had two sons: Sammi, who became Vice Minister of Rites, and Dŏksŏng, who achieved rank as Vice Minister of the Three Departments. By Park he had three children: Yuggyŏng, who became Minister of Genealogy; a daughter who married General Ŭ Inyŏl; and another who married Master Cho Yŏng. His descendants are numerous.

    His son Dŏksŏng, the Vice Minister, is my friend—spirited and fond of wine, wherever he served he left his name in honor. He came requesting this epitaph:

    *Behold the uprightness of this man,*
    *Behold his purity of heart.*
    *Behold his virtue, behold his fame—*
    *These were the measures of his age.*
    *Had he been given greater charge,*
    *How well he might have served the realm!*
    *Though he aided his sovereign long,*
    *In temples and halls wielding wise counsel,*
    *At seventy-six still vigorous,*
    *He retired with the clarity of the sage.*
    *O Minister Choe—*
    *May all generations cherish your example.*
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Wansan Choe were an eminent family of Gyeongju; Wansan refers to this region.
  - key: ''
    value: King Chungson reigned as both active and retired ruler, retaining significant influence even after his official abdication—a common practice in the Koryŏ court.
  - key: ''
    value: The military land allotment system (kyŏngban-jŏn) was designed to provide stable support for the military class but had become corrupted through inheritance disputes and unauthorized transfers.
